<typeStatus box="[551,645,2045,2069]" pageId="5" pageNumber="306">holotype</typeStatus>
collected from off 
<collectingRegion box="[214,303,2077,2101]" country="Indonesia" name="Sumatera Utara" pageId="5" pageNumber="306">Sumatra</collectingRegion>
at depth 
<quantity box="[407,533,2077,2101]" metricMagnitude="2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.5" metricValueMax="5.81" metricValueMin="5.1899999999999995" pageId="5" pageNumber="306" unit="m" value="550.0" valueMax="581.0" valueMin="519.0">
519– 
<specimenCount box="[462,533,2077,2101]" pageId="5" pageNumber="306" type="generic">581 m</specimenCount>
</quantity>
. 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[813,943,221,245]" pageId="5" pageNumber="306">Etymology.</emphasis>
The specific name is combination of two Greek words, 
<emphasis box="[888,971,253,277]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="306">brachys</emphasis>
short and 
<emphasis box="[1077,1133,254,277]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="306">soma</emphasis>
body, referring to its relatively short and stout body.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="5" pageNumber="306" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="5.[813,1452,221,2143]" pageId="5" pageNumber="306">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[813,960,349,373]" pageId="5" pageNumber="306">Comparison.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authority="Ho &amp; Satria, 2015" authorityName="Ho &amp; Satria" authorityYear="2015" box="[967,1211,349,373]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Chaunacidae" genus="Chaunax" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lophiiformes" pageId="5" pageNumber="306" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="brachysomus" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[967,1211,349,373]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="306">Chaunax brachysomus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[1217,1302,350,373]" pageId="5" pageNumber="306" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
is one of four 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Lowe" authorityYear="1846" box="[813,909,381,405]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Chaunacidae" genus="Chaunax" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lophiiformes" pageId="5" pageNumber="306" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[813,909,381,405]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="306">Chaunax</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species that have a uniformly pink or red colour when fresh and are uniformly pale when preserved, the other three species being 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Ho, Roberts &amp; Stewart" authorityYear="2013" box="[1039,1166,446,469]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Chaunacidae" genus="Chaunax" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lophiiformes" pageId="5" pageNumber="306" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="russatus">
<emphasis box="[1039,1166,446,469]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="306">C. russatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Ho, Roberts &amp; Stewart" authorityYear="2013" box="[1184,1304,445,469]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Chaunacidae" genus="Chaunax" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lophiiformes" pageId="5" pageNumber="306" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="mulleus">
<emphasis box="[1184,1304,445,469]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="306">C. mulleus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Lloyd" authorityYear="1909" box="[1365,1451,446,469]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Chaunacidae" genus="Chaunax" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lophiiformes" pageId="5" pageNumber="306" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="apus">
<emphasis box="[1365,1451,446,469]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="306">C. apus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(long-term preservation may cause loss of colour pattern in other species as well). It can be easily distinguished from the above-mentioned species by its large head, short tail, and few gill rakers (see 
<tableCitation box="[1078,1160,573,597]" captionStart="Table 2" captionStartId="3.[113,168,189,211]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="Table 2. Meristic data of two new species and three Chaunax species newly recorded from Indonesia. Values are provided as right side/ left side when different." pageId="5" pageNumber="306">Table 2</tableCitation>
for detailed comparison).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="5" pageNumber="306" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="5.[813,1452,221,2143]" pageId="5" pageNumber="306">
Although 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Ho &amp; Shao" authorityYear="2010" box="[931,1089,637,661]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Chaunacidae" genus="Chaunax" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lophiiformes" pageId="5" pageNumber="306" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="nudiventer">
<emphasis box="[931,1089,637,661]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="306">C. nudiventer</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was characterised by its large irregular greenish spots (
<bibRefCitation author="Ho H-C &amp; Shao K-T" box="[1070,1257,669,693]" pageId="5" pageNumber="306" pagination="53 - 61" refId="ref6619" refString="Ho H-C &amp; Shao K-T (2010) A new species of Chaunax (Lophiiformes: Chaunacidae) from the western South Pacific, with comments on C. latipunctatus. Zootaxa, 2445: 53 - 61." type="journal article" year="2010">Ho &amp; Shao, 2010</bibRefCitation>
), some individuals were found to be uniformly pinkish (Ho, pers. obser.). It differs from 
<taxonomicName authority="Ho &amp; Satria, 2015" authorityName="Ho &amp; Satria" authorityYear="2015" box="[945,1115,733,757]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Chaunacidae" genus="Chaunax" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lophiiformes" pageId="5" pageNumber="306" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="brachysomus" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[945,1115,733,757]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="306">C. brachysomus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[1120,1203,734,757]" pageId="5" pageNumber="306" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
in having a large naked area on the ventral surface and relatively more lateral-line neuromasts in the lateral-line proper (39–57, vs. 
<quantity box="[1359,1417,797,821]" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="8.382" pageId="5" pageNumber="306" unit="in" value="33.0">33 in</quantity>
<emphasis box="[1427,1452,798,821]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="306">C.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authorityName="Ho &amp; Satria" authorityYear="2015" box="[813,954,829,853]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Chaunacidae" genus="Chaunax" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lophiiformes" pageId="5" pageNumber="306" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="brachysomus">
<emphasis box="[813,954,829,853]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="306">brachysomus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
), upper preopercular series (three to five, vs. two), and pectoral series (15–17, vs. 12 or 13).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="5.[813,1452,221,2143]" pageId="5" pageNumber="306">
The presence of mixed broad- and narrow-based spinules on the dorsal surfaces is common in members of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Lowe" authorityYear="1846" box="[1348,1444,957,981]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Chaunacidae" genus="Chaunax" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lophiiformes" pageId="5" pageNumber="306" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1348,1444,957,981]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="306">Chaunax</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. These broad-based spinules are usually difficult to see without magnification, except for these pinkish species which have contract colouration among these two forms of spinules (e.g., more transparent, compared to these narrow-based spinules which are creamy white) and are easy to see. Thus far, 
<taxonomicName authority="Ho &amp; Satria, 2015" authorityName="Ho &amp; Satria" authorityYear="2015" box="[855,1027,1149,1173]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Chaunacidae" genus="Chaunax" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lophiiformes" pageId="5" pageNumber="306" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="brachysomus" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[855,1027,1149,1173]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="306">C. brachysomus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[1032,1116,1150,1173]" pageId="5" pageNumber="306" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
is the only member with mixed broad- and narrow-based spinules on the ventral surface. All other 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Lowe" authorityYear="1846" box="[922,1019,1213,1237]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Chaunacidae" genus="Chaunax" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lophiiformes" pageId="5" pageNumber="306" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[922,1019,1213,1237]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="306">Chaunax</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species are either naked in this region or have uniformly short spinules.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
